<TITLE> Prodi condemns talk of troop pullout from Lebanon </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ROME, March 14 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi on Friday condemned a former defence minister's call for a withdrawal of Italian troops from a UN mission in Lebanon, and the ex-minister's comments drew protests from Beirut. Lebanon's Parliament Speaker Nabih Berri summoned Italy's ambassador in Beirut to seek clarification of "dangerous" remarks by Antonio Martino, defence minister under Silvio Berlusconi's last government from 2001 to 2006. Martino had told Reuters in an interview published on Thursday he favoured a drastic reduction or complete withdrawal of Italy's "perfectly unneeded" troops from Lebanon. He said he wanted to become defence minister again if Berlusconi won April elections, and outlined his policy ideas. "I would reduce our presence in Lebanon drastically, if not cancel it all, and send troops to Afghanistan and to Iraq, where they are needed," Martino said, adding that he would only send military trainers to Iraq, not combat troops, if made minister. Berri's office said in a statement the Lebanese were "adamant" that Italian troops remain, partly "to stop Israeli aggressions against Lebanon". Prodi called Martino's words "irresponsible". "The comments by former defence minister Antonio Martino about a future withdrawal from Lebanon and a return to Iraq are extremely serious," Prodi told reporters in Brussels. He added that, although Martino wanted to become defence minister again, "I think that he won't be after these comments". In the interview, Martino said "it's not a given" that he would become Berlusconi's defence minister. He did not claim to be representing Berlusconi or his policy ideas. Foreign Minister Massimo D'Alema criticised Martino's call for a renewed effort in Iraq, less than two years after Italy withdrew from the unpopular mission. "There's something ridiculous about all this, especially when even the Americans are starting to show a willingness to withdraw," D'Alema sa
